  "response": "While there hasn't been an official statement from Hershey (the maker of Ice Breakers) explicitly stating *why* Ice Breakers Liquid Ice was discontinued, here's a breakdown of the likely contributing factors based on general market trends and product lifecycles:\n\n*   **Low Demand/Poor Sales:** This is the most common reason for discontinuing any product. If Liquid Ice wasn't selling well enough to justify its production, distribution, and marketing costs, Hershey would likely cut it.\n*   **Competition:** The breath freshener and mint market is very competitive. Other products might have been performing better in terms of sales and customer preference.\n*   **Product Formulation/Shelf Life Issues:** Liquid products can be more challenging to maintain in terms of shelf stability and prevent leakage or separation. If there were issues with the product's formulation leading to quality concerns or higher costs, it could have been a factor.\n*   **Focus on Core Products:** Companies often streamline their product lines to focus on the most profitable and popular items. Hershey might have decided to concentrate on their traditional Ice Breakers mints and gum.\n*   **Market Trends:** Consumer preferences change over time. Perhaps the popularity of liquid breath fresheners waned, or new types of breath freshening products emerged that were more appealing to consumers.\n*   **Packaging/Distribution Challenges:** Liquid Ice came in a unique dispenser. If there were problems with the packaging (e.g., difficulty in manufacturing, leakage issues, or high costs), it could have influenced the decision to discontinue.\n*   **Cost of Production:** It may have been more expensive to make Liquid Ice than other Ice Breakers products. If the profit margin wasn't high enough, it could have been discontinued.\n\nIn short, a combination of factors related to sales, competition, production costs, and market trends likely led to the discontinuation of Ice Breakers Liquid Ice